post_text:
Pandemic EBT
Due to Coronavirus (COVID-19), children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals at school will get extra food benefits. These food benefits are called Pandemic EBT or P-EBT benefits. P-EBT benefits help families in California buy food when schools are closed because of the coronavirus emergency.

Families will get up to $365 per eligible child on their P-EBT card to use on food and groceries.

Families with children who get CalFresh, Medi-Cal or Foster Care benefits do not need to apply. Most will get their P-EBT card in the mail during the month of May. P-EBT cards will begin arriving around May 12, 2020.

Families with children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals and who do not get their P-EBT card in the mail by about May 22, 2020 must apply online before June 30, 2020. The online application will be available beginning May 22, 2020 at ca.p-ebt.org.
https://www.cdss.ca.gov/home/pandemic-ebt

Online Athletic Clearance Instructions
Visit Website: www.AthleticClearance.com (from smart phone or computer)
Create Username & Password (Watch YouTube Video Guide on website)
Login to the site.
Select “New Clearance”
Choose the school year in which the student plans to participate.This is the 2020-2021 school year.
Select sport.
Complete all required fields for Student Information, Education History, Medical History, and Signature Forms.

FINAL CLEARANCE

Website will indicate you are ‘cleared’ (‘status’ will change to ‘cleared’)
You will receive an email indicating the status of your clearance.

California Youth Crisis Line
March 18 at 2:45 PM ·

During these difficult and stressful times, we would like to remind all of California's youth, youth allies, and families that our California Youth Crisis Line will remain open to take calls, chats, and texts 24/7. So if you are feeling anxiety, stress, depression or would like to talk about your feelings surrounding COVID-19, quarantine, social distancing or anything at all, you can reach us at 800 843 5200 or at calyouth.org/cycl. Please remember that the mental health effects of COVID-19 are as important to address as the physical health effects and that you're not alone during this time. Stay safe, be healthy, use common sense. #MentalHealth #California #Covid19 #Quarantine #Youth

post_text:
Hello,

After many conversations with many superintendents throughout Southern California and aligned with the National and State Emergencies that are now in place, the decision has been made to close Helendale Schools effective on Monday, March 16 due to the threat of the spread of the COVID-19 virus. There will be no Saturday School on March 14th. We will be closed until March 20th initially and will review the need for further closures by the end of next week.

We will continue to communicate with our Helendale Families through our Aeries Communication with updates. You can also check for updates on our website at www.helendalesd.com.

At this point in time the district will be closed through at least March 20th when it will be re-evaluated regarding the issue of the COVID-19 virus. All districts within the high desert will be closing effective this coming Monday, March 16.
